Europe
------
[1] ECDC report
Date: May 2013
Source: ECDC Surveillance Report [edited]
http://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/publications/Publications/measles-rubella-monitoring-may-2013.pdf


Main developments
-----------------
The 30 contributing countries (29 EU/EEA countries and Croatia) reported 8127 cases of measles during the last 12 month period (April 2012 to March 2013). (Luxembourg did not report for 3 [months] of the 12 month reporting period. The Netherlands did not report data for February and March 2013, and Iceland did not report data for March 2013).

France, Germany, Italy, Romania, Spain, and the United Kingdom accounted for 95 per cent of the cases in the last 12 month period. 14 countries met the elimination target of less than one case of measles per million population during the last 12 months.

[In comparison Poland and Romania accounted for 99 per cent of all reported rubella cases in the same 12 month period. Romania has reported an average of 7 cases per month since August 2012, indicating that the nationwide epidemic that affected more than 20 000 people is now over. Poland is experiencing a nationwide rubella epidemic. Since August 2012, Poland has reported over 95 per cent of all rubella cases in the EU/EEA. The highest notifications have been among adolescents aged 15-19 years. Women represented 39.6 per cent of the case-based reports in the 15-44 year age group.]

66 per cent of the cases had a positive result in a measles laboratory test (serology, virus detection, or isolation). Of the 7757 cases for which information on vaccination status was available, 82 per cent were unvaccinated. In the target group for routine childhood MMR vaccination (1-4 year olds), 78 per cent of the cases were unvaccinated.

No measles-related deaths were reported during the period April 2012-March 2013 but 6 cases were complicated by acute measles encephalitis.

Epidemic intelligence reports
-----------------------------
- In the United Kingdom, measles transmission continues in England and Wales.
- Public Health England has launched a catch-up measles vaccination campaign that aims to immunise an estimated 330 000 unvaccinated people in the 10-16 year old age group. The plan is to halt the outbreak before the school start in autumn.

Surveillance data
-----------------
The enhanced measles surveillance data were retrieved from The European Surveillance System (TESSY) on 30 Apr 2013. The analysis covered the 12 month period from April 2012 to March 2013. All the 30 contributing countries (29 EU/EEA countries and Croatia) reported case-based data for the period. Data were missing for 3 months (November, December, and January) of the 12 month reporting period for Luxemburg, while the Netherlands did not report data for February and March 2013; Iceland did not report data for March 2013.

During the period April 2012 to March 2013, 8127 cases of measles were reported. The highest notification rate was among infants under one year of age (224.6 cases per million population), followed by children aged between 1 and 4 years (101.1 cases per million population) (Figure 2 -- available at the source URL above). The number of reported cases in March 2013 was about half of that reported for the same month in 2012, and the expected increase in cases normally associated with the peak transmission season of measles in the spring has so far not been observed in the 2013 data. 66 per cent of the cases had a positive result in a measles laboratory test (serology, virus detection, or isolation) but variations were observed between countries.

Vaccination status was known for 7757 (95 per cent) of the 8127 reported cases. Of these, 82 per cent (6389 cases) were unvaccinated, 12.5 per cent (973) had received one dose of measles vaccine, 3.5 per cent (273) had received 2 or more doses, and 1.6 per cent (122) had received an unknown number of doses. The proportion of unvaccinated cases was high across all age groups. Among the 1-4 year olds, which is the age group targeted by routine childhood vaccination programmes, 78 per cent of the cases were unvaccinated.

Over the last 12 months, 6 cases were complicated by acute measles encephalitis. No measles-related deaths were reported. [These data are presented as tables, graphs, and maps. Interested readers should access the original document via the source URL above. - Mod.CP]

